  "prompt": "A bag contains 5 white, 7 red and 8 black balls. If four balls are drawn one by one without replacement, what is the probability of getting all white balls?",
  "response": "To find the probability of drawing 4 white balls from a bag that contains 5 white, 7 red, and 8 black balls, we start by determining the total number of balls in the bag:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Total balls} = 5 + 7 + 8 = 20\n\\]\n\nNext, we need to consider the event of drawing 4 white balls without replacement. Let's calculate the number of ways to draw 4 white balls from 5 available:\n\n1. For the first draw, the probability of drawing a white ball is:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{5}{20}\n\\]\n\n2. For the second draw, after successfully drawing one white ball, there are now 4 white balls left and a total of 19 balls:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{4}{19}\n\\]\n\n3. For the third draw, the probability becomes:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{3}{18}\n\\]\n\n4. Finally, for the fourth draw:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{2}{17}\n\\]\n\nNow, we multiply these probabilities together to find the probability of drawing 4 white balls in succession:\n\n\\[\nP(\\text{all white}) = \\frac{5}{20} \\times \\frac{4}{19} \\times \\frac{3}{18} \\times \\frac{2}{17}\n\\]\n\nCalculating this step by step:\n\n\\[\nP(\\text{all white}) = \\frac{5 \\times 4 \\times 3 \\times 2}{20 \\times 19 \\times 18 \\times 17}\n\\]\n\nCalculating the numerator:\n\n\\[\n5 \\times 4 = 20,\n\\]\n\n\\[\n20 \\times 3 = 60,\n\\]\n\n\\[\n60 \\times 2 = 120.\n\\]\n\nCalculating the denominator:\n\n\\[\n20 \\times 19 = 380,\n\\]\n\n\\[\n380 \\times 18 = 6840,\n\\]\n\n\\[\n6840 \\times 17 = 116280.\n\\]\n\nNow we have:\n\n\\[\nP(\\text{all white}) = \\frac{120}{116280}.\n\\]\n\nNext, we simplify the fraction:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{120}{116280} = \\frac{1}{969}.\n\\]\n\nThus, the probability of drawing all white balls when 4 balls are drawn one by one without replacement is:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\frac{1}{969}}.\n\\]",
